1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,730
Many, many potentially powerful people let petty, small, insignificant things block their way to achievement.

2
00:00:07,840 --> 00:00:09,809
Let's look at four examples.

3
00:00:09,840 --> 00:00:11,250
1.

4
00:00:11,600 --> 00:00:14,370
What does it take to make a good speech?

5
00:00:15,200 --> 00:00:21,410
Just about everyone wishes he had the ability to do a first-class job of speaking in public.

6
00:00:21,600 --> 00:00:24,049
But most people don't get their wish.

7
00:00:24,240 --> 00:00:27,250
Most folks are lousy public speakers.

8
00:00:27,520 --> 00:00:28,130
Why?

9
00:00:28,320 --> 00:00:29,650
The reason is simple.

10
00:00:29,840 --> 00:00:37,010
Most people concentrate on the small, trivial things of speaking at the expense of the big, important things.

11
00:00:37,440 --> 00:00:43,250
In preparing to give a talk, most people give themselves a host of mental instructions,

12
00:00:43,440 --> 00:00:49,170
like, I've got to remember to stand straight, don't move around and don't use your hands,

13
00:00:49,360 --> 00:00:55,089
don't let the audience see you use your notes, remember, don't make mistakes in grammar,

14
00:00:55,089 --> 00:01:00,049
especially don't say, for he and I, say, for him and me,

15
00:01:00,240 --> 00:01:06,370
be sure your tie is straight, speak loud but not too loud, and so on and so on.

16
00:01:06,960 --> 00:01:10,529
Now, what happens when the speaker gets up to speak?

17
00:01:10,640 --> 00:01:15,890
He's scared because he's given himself a terrific list of things not to do.

18
00:01:16,080 --> 00:01:22,210
He gets confused in his talk and finds himself silently asking, have I made a mistake?

19
00:01:22,480 --> 00:01:24,770
He is, in brief, a flop.

20
00:01:24,960 --> 00:01:36,370
He's a flop because he concentrated on the petty, trivial, relatively unimportant qualities of a good speaker and failed to concentrate on the big things that make a good speaker.

21
00:01:36,880 --> 00:01:43,010
knowledge of what he's going to talk about, and an intense desire to tell it to other people.

22
00:01:43,600 --> 00:01:49,730
The real test of a speaker is not did he stand straight or did he make any mistakes in grammar,

23
00:01:49,840 --> 00:01:54,049
but rather did the audience get the points he wanted to put across.

24
00:01:54,480 --> 00:01:57,809
Most of our top speakers have petty defects.

25
00:01:57,920 --> 00:02:00,850
Some of them even have unpleasant voices.

26
00:02:01,200 --> 00:02:07,569
Some of the most sought-after speakers in America would flunk a speech course taught by the old negative,

27
00:02:07,760 --> 00:02:10,529
don't do this and don't do that method.

28
00:02:10,960 --> 00:02:15,089
Yet all these successful public speakers have one thing in common.

29
00:02:15,360 --> 00:02:21,170
They have something to say and they feel a burning desire for other people to hear it.

30
00:02:21,520 --> 00:02:26,610
Don't let concern with trivia keep you from speaking successfully in public.

